Children and Youth Studies Program

# CHST 3430: Children and the Media - 32657

Spring 2016: Tuesdays and Thursdays 02:15pm-3:30pm

5606 James Hall

Aysenur Ataman

aataman@csi.cuny.edu

This course will introduce students to a range of issues, research and practices concerning children and media of all sorts. It will also teach students to read and analyze visual media for cultural tropes, especially those concerning youth and children. The course includes in-depth analysis of U.S. media as well as discussion of youth, children, and media from an international and cross-cultural perspective. In addition to scholarly articles and readings, students will become media critics themselves by analyzing digital media for cultural content, socialization strategies, and moralizing tropes.

# **Required text:** All readings are on Blackboard.

# Learning Objectives:

-To examine the history and current practice of media effects _and_ cultural research on children and youth.

# -To analyze advertising and marketing practices aimed at children and youth.

-To analyze various representations in media messages aimed at children and youth.

-To examine how young people use media in agentic ways to shape their worlds and social change.

# Attendance policy:

Attendance is expected in this course.  Materials are presented in class that are unavailable in assigned readings, so it is necessary that you attend every class meeting. There are no texts or notes that can substitute for the discussions and interaction that will take place in class.

If you are not in attendance during a particular class period it is _your_ responsibility to get notes and/or other materials from your fellow students.  It is not the professor&#39;s responsibility to fill you in on what you missed.

Lateness to class is rude and disruptive.  If you are more than 15 minutes late to class you will be asked to do more work in class for the day. More than 3 absences and your grade will drop.

CELL PHONES  Cell phone use is not permitted in class, not even as a reading device. Texting is not tolerated and will result in point loss for attendance and participation grade.

Weekly Discussion Forum (on Blackboard):

Each week, please prepare 1-2 questions based on the readings and the thoughts that they have evoked. These will be posted to Blackboard as homework. You will then post comments to at least two other students&#39; posts. Ideally, you will bring your questions to class and help us discuss the topic together.



Plagiarism and Academic Misconduct:

The faculty and administration of Brooklyn College support **an environment free from cheating and plagiarism**.  Each student is responsible for being aware of what constitutes cheating and plagiarism and for avoiding both.  The complete text of the CUNY academic integrity policy and the Brooklyn College procedure for implementing that policy can be found at this site:   [http://www.brooklyn.cuny.edu/bc/policies](http://www.brooklyn.cuny.edu/bc/policies) If a faculty member suspects a violation of academic integrity and, upon investigation, confirms that violation, or if the student admits the violation, the faculty member MUST report the violation.



In order to receive **disability-related academic accommodations** students must first be registered with the Center for Student Disability Services.  Students who have a documented disability or suspect they may have a disability are invited to set up an appointment with the Director of the Center for Student Disability Services at 718 951 5538.  If you have already registered with the Center for Student Disability Services please provide your professor with the course accommodation form and discuss your specific accommodation with him.
